Another word for “field” in this context is “meso-level social order.”
The central premise of field theory is that “most of social life occurs in arenas where actors take one another into account in their actions.”

Field theory recognizes a dynamic and dialectic relationship between the norms and constraints of the field, where interaction takes place and the ever-shifting agency of the actors within that field.
Phenomenology and symbolic interactionism, rather than rationalism, are the primary frameworks through which field theorists explain the behavior and agency of actors.
